See: https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/subplots_axes_and_figures/subplots_demo.html¶

# Import Libraries
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

In [2]:
# Test data to plot
x = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 400)
y = np.sin(x ** 2)

Just One Subplot¶

In [3]:
# subplots() without arguments returns a Figure and a single Axes
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(x, y)
ax.set_title('A single plot')
Out[3]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'A single plot')

Stacking Subplots¶

In [4]:
# Vertically Stacked Subplots with one axs
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2)
fig.suptitle('Vertically Stacked Subplots')
axs[0].plot(x, y)
axs[1].plot(x, y)

In [8]:
# Stacking Subplots in two directions.
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2)

axs[0, 0].plot(x, y)
axs[0, 0].set_title('Axis [0, 0]')
axs[0, 1].plot(x, y, 'tab:orange')
axs[0, 1].set_title('Axis [0, 1]')
axs[1, 0].plot(x, y, 'tab:green')
axs[1, 0].set_title('Axis [1, 0]')
axs[1, 1].plot(x, y, 'tab:red')
axs[1, 1].set_title('Axis [1, 1]')

# Set outer labels and hide the top xlabels and the ticks for the right plots
for ax in axs.flat:
    ax.set(xlabel='x-label', ylabel='y-label')
    ax.label_outer()
In [9]:
# Use tuple-unpacking to assign subplot settings
# Share x per column, y per row
fig, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2, 2)
fig.suptitle('Shared X Y Labels')

ax1.plot(x, y)
ax2.plot(x, y**2, 'tab:orange')
ax3.plot(x, -y, 'tab:green')
ax4.plot(x, -y**2, 'tab:red')

for ax in fig.get_axes():
    ax.label_outer()
In [10]:
# Shared x or y axis by using sharex or sharey

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True)
fig.suptitle('Aligning x-axis using sharex')
ax1.plot(x, y)
ax2.plot(x + 1, -y)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(3, sharex=True, sharey=True)
fig.suptitle('Sharing both axes')
axs[0].plot(x, y ** 2)
axs[1].plot(x, 0.3 * y, 'o') # ploting o's
axs[2].plot(x, y, '+') # ploting +'s
Out[10]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1b7ad770ec0>]
In [11]:
# Use the label_outer to remove labels and ticks from subplots
fig = plt.figure()
gs = fig.add_gridspec(3, hspace=0)
axs = gs.subplots(sharex=True, sharey=True)
fig.suptitle('Sharing Axes, Out Label Only')

axs[0].plot(x, y ** 2)
axs[1].plot(x, 0.3 * y, 'o')
axs[2].plot(x, y, '+')

#Hide x labels and ticks for all but bottom label.
for ax in axs:
    ax.label_outer()
In [12]:
#sharex and sharey also accept 'row' and 'col'.
fig = plt.figure()
gs = fig.add_gridspec(2, 2, hspace=0, wspace=0)
(ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4) = gs.subplots(sharex='col', sharey='row')
fig.suptitle('Grid Spec Plot, Shared Axis')

ax1.plot(x, y)
ax2.plot(x, y**2, 'tab:orange')
ax3.plot(x + 1, -y, 'tab:green')
ax4.plot(x + 2, -y**2, 'tab:red')

for ax in fig.get_axes():
    ax.label_outer()
In [13]:
# Not all plots in the subplot have to share the axis
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2)

axs[0, 0].plot(x, y)
axs[0, 0].set_title("Main")

axs[1, 0].plot(x, y**2)
axs[1, 0].set_title("Shares xlabel with Main")

axs[1, 0].sharex(axs[0, 0])
                    
axs[0, 1].plot(x + 1, y + 1)
axs[0, 1].set_title("Non-shared Axis")

axs[1, 1].plot(x + 2, y + 2)
axs[1, 1].set_title("Non-shared Axis")

fig.tight_layout()

Polar Axes¶

In [14]:
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, subplot_kw=dict(projection='polar'))
ax1.plot(x, y)
ax2.plot(x, y ** 2)
plt.show()
